      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clemens, Piazza And a Bad Call</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>James O Chamberlain letter holds any pitcher who hits a batter in the head should be ejected (Oct 24 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Baseball Justice'' (editorial, Oct. 24):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Baseball Justice'' (editorial, Oct. 24):</p>
        <p>Ever since Roger Clemens beaned Mike Piazza this summer, the TV and radio talk shows have been fueling the flames for a confrontation. It should be no surprise that something happened on Sunday. There is only one way to stop this circus and preserve baseball's image: a pitcher should automatically be ejected whenever a batter is hit in the head.</p>
        <p>Such a rule would not dwell on the question of whether the pitcher deliberately tried to hit the batter. In fact, it protects a pitcher from just such an accusation. No pitcher would purposely try to hit a batter's head when he knew that ejection was the automatic result.</p>
        <p>That a beaning is accidental does not make ejection too harsh a remedy. A ball is a lethal weapon in the hand of a professional ballplayer. If a pitcher begins to lose his control, he should think twice about throwing high and inside.</p>
        <p>JAMES O. CHAMBERLAIN  Forest Hills, Queens, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
